<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910813-0016</DOCNO><DOCID>910813-0016.</DOCID><HL>   Kennametal Denies   Charges It Sold Iraq   Military Equipment</HL><DATE>08/13/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18</SO><CO>   KMT</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)FACTORY EQUIPMENT (FAC)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><NS>TRADE ISSUES (TRD)</NS><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)</GV><RE>IRAQ (IZ)MIDDLE EAST (ML)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LATROBE, Pa. -- Kennametal Inc. continued to dismissallegations that it sold military-related equipment to Iraqin violation of export laws, reiterating its claim that itdid nothing &quot;illegal or improper.&quot;   The company has been under investigation by a jointcongressional subcommittee for allegedly selling to Iraqmilitary-related technology and machine tools used to makemunitions.</LP><TEXT>   Kennametal said it had completed by early 1991 &quot;exhaustivereviews&quot; that &quot;convinced company officials that Kennametalhas acted properly in all matters questioned.&quot; Kennametalsaid it sold to Iraq in 1989 and 1990 less than $900,000 ofstandard metal-working products, used for a wide range ofmachining operations, before President Bush banned trade withIraq in August 1990. The company said its inquiries &quot;revealedno sales of products or services of any kind directly orindirectly to Iraq after Aug. 2, 1990.&quot;   The company accused the subcommittee of making no attemptto contact Kennametal before a hearing Aug. 1, thereforeallowing &quot;false allegations&quot; to stand. Rep. Charles Rose (D.,N.C.), who is leading the subcommittee hearings with Rep. SamGejdenson (D., Conn.), has said he would be &quot;glad&quot; to hearfrom Kennametal officials, who will testify when hearingsreconvene in September.   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,Kennametal shares closed at $31.625, down $3.50.</TEXT></DOC>